      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why S Is the Most Valuable Utility Tile</h2>
      <p>Don't be fooled by S's 1-point face value. In competitive Scrabble, S is treated as worth 8-10 points of strategic value because of its hooking ability. Adding S to the end of an existing word while simultaneously playing your own word perpendicular to it creates two scoring words in a single turn — often yielding 30-50+ total points.</p>
      <p>There are four S tiles in the bag, but tournament players guard them jealously. Using S in the middle of an ordinary word (like BEST or FAST) wastes its hooking potential. The golden rule: never use S unless it earns you at least 8-10 points more than your next-best play without it.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing S-Words</h2>
      <p>S rewards patience and board awareness. Here's how to maximise your S-tile value:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Save S for hooks:</strong> The default strategy is to hold S unless playing it scores 8+ points more than your alternative. A well-timed hook on a triple-word square can score 40+ points in a single play.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use S for bingos:</strong> The one exception to saving S is when it enables a 7-letter bingo. The 50-point bonus justifies using S in any position. S appears in thousands of valid 7-letter words.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>SCH- words for power:</strong> SCHMALTZ (24), SCHMUCK (20), SCHERZO (21) — the SCH- cluster combines S with high-value consonants for strong standalone scores.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>SQU- for explosive scoring:</strong> SQUEEZE (25), SQUEEZY (28) — when you have both S and QU together, these words deliver massive points while solving the Q problem.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Short S+X words:</strong> SAX, SOX, SIX, SEX — all score 10 points for just 3 letters. Perfect for premium square targeting when the board is tight.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Art of S-Hooking</h2>
      <p>S-hooking is the single most important scoring technique in competitive Scrabble. Here's how it works:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Front hooks:</strong> S placed before an existing word (S + CARE = SCARE, S + TALK = STALK). You form a new word while the original word remains valid.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Back hooks:</strong> S added to the end of any noun or verb (CAT + S = CATS). This is the most common hook — nearly universal.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Double scoring:</strong> The key is that you score BOTH words — the original word with S added AND your perpendicular word. Both count toward your turn total.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When S Should Be Played Immediately</h2>
      <p>Despite the "save S" rule, there are clear situations where playing S immediately is correct: when it enables a bingo (50-point bonus), when it reaches a triple-word square that won't be available next turn, or when you're in the endgame and tile counting shows S won't find a better opportunity. Don't be so precious with S that you miss scoring windows. The best players know when the rule applies and when the exception applies.</p>

